<p>Your product needs <strong>identity verification</strong>. Maybe you're a fintech launching KYC, a marketplace adding seller verification, or a platform that needs age gating. The first question: build or buy?</p>

<p>In 2026, the answer has changed. Open-source biometric libraries and managed APIs make building significantly cheaper than it was even two years ago. But "build" doesn't mean what it used to — the real question is where on the spectrum you land.</p>

<h2>The Spectrum</h2>

<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Option</th><th>Cost</th><th>Control</th><th>Time to launch</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Build from scratch (train models, write inference)</td><td>$500K+</td><td>Total</td><td>12-18 months</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Assemble from open-source (InsightFace + custom server)</td><td>$20-50K</td><td>High</td><td>2-4 months</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Open-source platform (OpenBiometrics self-hosted)</td><td>$0-5K</td><td>High</td><td>1-2 weeks</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Managed API (OpenBiometrics Cloud, Onfido, Jumio)</td><td>$29-5K/mo</td><td>Medium</td><td>1-2 days</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Enterprise vendor (IDEMIA, Innovatrics)</td><td>$50-500K/yr</td><td>Low</td><td>3-6 months</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>When to Build (Self-Host)</h2>

<p>Self-hosting makes sense when:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Regulatory requirements</strong> — biometric data cannot leave your infrastructure (GDPR, financial regulations)</li>
  <li><strong>Volume economics</strong> — at 1M+ verifications/month, API pricing exceeds infrastructure costs</li>
  <li><strong>Customization</strong> — you need to modify the pipeline (custom models, specific preprocessing)</li>
  <li><strong>Latency</strong> — on-premise or edge deployment with &lt;50ms requirements</li>
</ul>

<p>With OpenBiometrics, self-hosting is a Docker container:</p>

<pre><code>docker run -p 8000:8000 ghcr.io/openbiometrics/api:latest

# Same API, same SDKs, same code — just different base URL
const ob = new OpenBiometrics({'{'}
  apiKey: 'any-value',
  baseUrl: 'http://your-server:8000',
{'}'});
</code></pre>

<h2>When to Use a Managed API</h2>

<p>Managed APIs make sense when:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Speed to market</strong> — you need identity verification this week, not this quarter</li>
  <li><strong>Small team</strong> — no bandwidth to manage GPU servers, model updates, scaling</li>
  <li><strong>Low volume</strong> — under 100K verifications/month, API pricing is cheaper than infrastructure</li>
  <li><strong>Compliance</strong> — the vendor handles SOC 2, GDPR data processing agreements</li>
</ul>

